# UI Development: Strict Feature-Sliced Design

Use FSD as a hard constraint for every UI change. Do not adapt to the current project structure if it conflicts with FSD.

## Mandatory architecture

- Use only FSD layers: `app`, `pages`, `widgets`, `features`, `entities`, `shared`.
- `app` and `shared` do not contain business slices.
- Slice names are business/domain-oriented (not technical names like `components`, `hooks`, `types`).
- Inside slices, use purpose-based segments: `ui`, `model`, `api`, `lib`, `config`.

## Dependency and import rules (strict)

- Import only from lower layers (`pages -> widgets/features/entities/shared`, etc.).
- Same-layer cross-imports are forbidden.
- The only allowed same-layer exception is `entities` via `@x` public API notation.
- Inside one slice, use relative imports with full internal paths.
- Between slices/layers, use only the slice public API (never internal files).

## Public API rules (strict)

- Every slice must expose a single explicit public API entry point (an `index` file appropriate for the stack).
- No wildcard re-exports (`export *`) in slice public APIs.
- Never import from internal paths like `features/x/ui/...` from outside `features/x`.
- For `shared/ui` and `shared/lib`, expose APIs per module (for example `shared/ui/button`) instead of one global barrel.

## Templ style placement (strict)

- Keep style declarations (`css ...`) in a dedicated sibling file named `{module}.styles.templ`.
- Keep markup/components in the main `{module}.templ` file.
- Use the same package name in both files so style functions remain available without extra imports.
- Apply this convention consistently to every UI module in all FSD layers.

## Agent behavior for UI tasks

- First place/relocate code into the correct FSD layer and slice, then implement logic.
- If requested change violates FSD, perform an FSD-compliant restructure as part of the task.
- Keep slices independent and cohesive: no hidden coupling through utils or deep cross-links.
- Add/update public API files when creating or moving UI capabilities.
- In final response, explicitly confirm: layer placement, import direction, and public API compliance.

## Examples

```text
Good: pages/host-list imports widgets/host-table via widgets/host-table public API.
Bad: pages/host-list imports widgets/host-table/ui/table.templ directly.

Good: features/notes exposes only required symbols via its index API.
Bad: features/notes/index re-exports everything from model/ui with wildcard exports.
```
